          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Mexican condition</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Mexican President Claudia Sheinbaum hopes to <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/12/05/americas/mexico-sheinbaum-trump-deportation-intl-latam/index.html" target="_blank">negotiate</a> with U.S. President-elect Donald Trump to limit third-country deportees to Mexico, prioritizing Mexican nationals. She emphasized solidarity with migrants during a press conference while asserting Mexico's responsibility to support its citizens. She announced preparations with border state governors for potential mass deportations. Meanwhile, Mexico has intensified its actions against fentanyl trafficking and migrant flows, including a record fentanyl bust in Sinaloa.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Trump's team reiterated their focus on border security and deportations. Although Sheinbaum described a recent call with Trump as productive, she denied agreeing to close the border. In contrast, Panama has <a href="https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20241205-bahamas-rejects-trump-proposal-to-take-deported-migrants-1" target="_blank">refused</a> to accept deportees of non-Panamanian nationalities under the future Trump administration, citing adherence to international law. The Bahamas has said they will accept <a href="https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/bahamas-rejects-trump-proposal-to-take-in-deported-third-country-migrants/ar-AA1vkR5S?ocid=BingNewsSerp" target="_blank">no deportations</a> from the United States.</p>
        </mj-text>
