          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is ANZUS?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-10-3.jpg" alt="What is ANZUS?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The <a href="https://www.nma.gov.au/defining-moments/resources/anzus-treaty" target="_blank">ANZUS Treaty</a> is a security pact signed in 1951 between Australia, New Zealand, and the United States to ensure mutual defense in the Pacific region. The treaty was born out of post-World War II concerns, particularly about the spread of communism in the Pacific, and it committed each country to assist the others if one was attacked.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">However, in the 1980s, New Zealand’s decision to become a nuclear-free zone caused a rift, leading to the U.S. suspending its military commitments to New Zealand. As a result, ANZUS essentially became a bilateral agreement between the U.S. and Australia. ​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Today, while New Zealand still benefits from strong diplomatic ties with both nations, it is no longer involved in the treaty’s defense obligations. The ANZUS Treaty remains vital for Australia and the U.S., continuing to shape military cooperation and regional stability in the Indo-Pacific.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
